 - The key controls whether the LaunchedEffect block restarts. With key = userId (unchanged), the polling job does not restart.
 - Recomposition happens whenever collected state changes. Your UI collects the ViewModel state; when isApproved changes, Compose recomposes to reflect it. That’s expected and desired.

- Why you still see recompositions:
 - The polling emits a new Success(user) each cycle; the UI observes it and recomposes. This does not restart the LaunchedEffect, it only redraws.

- If you want to avoid recomposition when nothing changed:
 - Skip state updates if the relevant fields didn’t change:
 ```kotlin
 apiOperation.onSuccess { user ->
 val shouldUpdate = (state.value as? WaitingScreenState.Success)
 ?.user?.isApproved != user.isApproved
 if (shouldUpdate) {
 _state.update { WaitingScreenState.Success(user) }
 }
 }
 ```
 - Or use distinctUntilChanged on the stream:
 ```kotlin
 getSpecificUserUseCase(userId)
 .mapNotNull { it.getOrNull()?.isApproved } // adapt to your ApiOperation
 .distinctUntilChanged()
 .collect { /* fetch full user and update, or keep isApproved in state */ }
 ```

- Bottom line: key=userId prevents the effect from restarting; recomposition on isApproved change is normal and exactly how Compose updates the UI."}]}]}

